                                                                                                               SPORT BRIEFS
                                                
	Roadblock lsquo;cleared rsquo; for England players  London: The roadblock to the participation of Kevin Pietersen, Andrew Flintoff and teammates in the second edition of Indian Premier League seems to have been removed after the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) and the Professional Cricketers rsquo; Association agreed on a 15-day window for the players.  The duration agreed by the ECB and the PCA means players will be able to play in the first few rounds of the IPL, starting in April, before returning for the first Test against the West Indies starting at Lord rsquo;s on May 6.    
	 Butt snubbed  Karachi: PCB chairman Ejaz Butt has been snubbed by board patron-in-chief and Pakistan President Asif Ali Zardari who has asked him to consult the sports ministry rsquo;s constitution committee while suggesting amendments to the PCB constitution.
  Meanwhile, Chief selector Abdul Qadir has irked the Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) officials by going public with his idea of having separate Test and one-day teams with different captains, sources said.    
	 Warne poll  Melbourne: Shane Warne may not turn out to be as good a commentator as he was a bowler, if the result of a recent poll conducted by an Australian TV network is to be believed.  An Australian TV network asked people to vote whether former player Shane Warne was likely to prove as successful a TV commentator as he was a bowler. Of those who responded, 73 per cent said no and the rest said yes.     
	 CA contracts  Melbourne: Cricket Australia is on the verge of its biggest contractual shake-up following its team rsquo;s first home Test series defeat in 16 years. Up to eight contracts, valued at more than $2 million, are up for grabs as a result of several stars facing the chop or a salary downgrade, according to a report.    
	 New job  New Delhi: Sacked East Bengal coach Stanley Rozario is set to take over as the Salgaocar coach, according to sources in the Goan club. The Bangalorebased former Army coach will arive in Goa on Sunday to finalise the deal with Salgaocar officials. Interestingly, Rozario will replace Subhas Bhowmick, who recently quit Salgaocar to become the East Bengal coach.    
	 City transfer  Manchester: Manchester City completed the signing of England defender Wayne Bridge from Chelsea on Saturday for an undisclosed fee rumoured to be about pound;12 million.
  The 28-year-old left back passed his medical examination and agreed to a 3 1/2-year contract that British papers have suggested could make him the highest paid fullback in the world.  
